<section xml:id="sec-logical-arrays" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
<title>Logical Arrays</title>

		<p>
			These operations extend to matrices with an entry-by-entry comparison of matrices of the same size.
		</p>

		<example xml:id="ex_logic1"><p/>
		<title><em></em></title><p/>
			<sidebyside width="100%">
				<program language="matlab">
					<code>
						&gt;&gt; a = [0,1; 1,2], b = [0,0; 1,1]
					</code>
				</program>
			</sidebyside>

			<sidebyside width="100%">
				<program language="matlab">
					<code>
						a =
							0 1
							1 2

						b =
							0 0
							1 1
					</code>
				</program>
			</sidebyside>

			<p>
				with
			</p>

			<sidebyside width="100%">
				<program language="matlab">
					<code>
						&gt;&gt; a &amp; b, a | b, xor(a,b)
					</code>
				</program>
			</sidebyside>

			<p>
				returns
			</p>

			<sidebyside width="100%">
				<program language="matlab">
					<code>
						ans =
							0 0
							1 1
						
						ans =
							0 1
							1 1
						
						ans =
							0 1
							0 0
					</code>
				</program>
			</sidebyside>

		</example>

		<note>
			<p>
				One minor point to note is that while Matlab treats 0 as false, any other positive whole number is considered as true.  So, in this example, even though the <m>(2,2)</m> entry of a is a 2, it is considered as "true" for logical comparison.
			</p>
		</note>

</section>